// Regression test for a use-after-free when building an array literal.
//
// The ARRAY opcode popped its elements off the value stack into a Vec and then
// allocated the array object. Between the pop and the allocation the elements
// were no longer on the stack, so they were not reachable from any GC root: a
// collection triggered by the array allocation would free them, leaving the new
// array holding dangling pointers.
//
// `gcStress(true)` forces collection on every allocation, so the array
// allocation below deterministically collects while its elements are off the
// stack. The three boxes are then rebuilt as `p1`/`p2`/`p3`, which reuse the
// freed slots if the elements were wrongly collected — so a buggy build reads
// back 44/55/66 (or crashes) instead of 11/22/33.

gcStress(true);

type Box {
    v;
    init(x) {
        this.v = x;
    }
}

say a = [Box(11), Box(22), Box(33)];

say p1 = Box(44);
say p2 = Box(55);
say p3 = Box(66);

print(a[0].v); // expect: 11
print(a[1].v); // expect: 22
print(a[2].v); // expect: 33
